<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But why &quot;punish&quot; me <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How are you being punished? From the sound of it there are several items that could have dropped that you could have rolled on. Be happy for the Int/Wis casters that they got a drop that they can use. Next time perhaps you'll get something.<br>
<br>
Out of all the things that the Lady will drop a Bard can get (and USE), Crystalline Spear, Dragon Bone Bracelet, McVaxius' Horn of War [Bard ONLY], Runed Bolster Belt, and White Dragon Scales which is for your epic. Casters only get a chance at the Eyepatch, a very rare Kayruuls Mystic Pouch, and there is a Wiz Spell: Ice Comet that drops. There's a staff but its not for Pure Casters. If you ask me, by letting everyone roll on one of the only items that would be worth to an Int/Wis caster, you would be 'punishing' the casters.<br>
<br>
Even if the rules weren't reviewed before the raid, if they say only casters roll there shouldn't be an issue. It's their ball game. They are the Leader. It's their raid.<br>
<br>
Obviously there has been a LOT of discussion on this issue, as has been pointed out, and those who have been playing the game for a LONG time have come up with a solution that most seem to like. Why throw a wrench into it? Without casters you couldn't kill Vox to even get the eyepatch. <p>Qamgine Nighteagle<br>
Fearless Leader<br>
Incoming --- { Qamgine } --- Get Ready!<br>
If you even think of cooking me, there'll be trouble!<br>
aka: Q or FL<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usotvfarrnusno.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SOTVFarrnusno</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#8E9173>(9/17/02 12:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscouncildiscussions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=93.topic&index=8>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why be Greedy</span><hr size=1> Quote from my post when I took over Liaison Duties:<br>
<br>
&quot;Loot will be handled by rolling on a NBG status. If you can actively use it (as determined by me), then you can use it. I don't want any arguements about loot on the raid, if you are upset about the way something is handled, bring it up on the boards AFTER the raid. I am willing to talk through things of this nature to make people as happy as possible, but I will not do it on the fly in the middle of a raid.&quot;<br>
<br>
You did right to let it slide then, and bring it up on the boards.  This is exactly how I want things like this to proceed.  This way it is out in the open, and I can see what everyone thinks.  If there is an overwhelming response to change something, then I will very well consider the change.  So don't get after him for posting in this way, as that is exactly what I want.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
<br>
&quot;Again, I am not trying to stir controversy. I'm simply a little miffed that I didn't even get a chance to roll. And was VERY embarrased when I was basically shut down in front of a large group before I even had a chance to state a case. But if I had, it only would have made people angry and made me look like a loot hog. So, my pride is a little hurt, but I'll get over it. I only did this post as food-for-thought. You never know when something like this will happen to you.&quot;<br>
<br>
I want controversy, that is not a problem.  If I know there is an issue I can handle it, and the boards are the best way to do so.  Raids are not the right place to do them, so I thank you for letting it slide and bringing it to the boards like this.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
<br>
&quot;As far as the idea goes that a bard wouldn't wear this, well, it's just absurd. I mean, come on? &quot;Monk-item&quot; is the cry of the equipment message boards. And ideas such as &quot;a bard would never wear this&quot; only spreads the lie. This is a character that I have put alot of time and effort into, and have plans for. My enchanter-suit that I am working on will have some value in the future as it has been stated that when bards are &quot;re-balanced&quot; they are looking at bards as a caster class. Absor even said he always felt that bards were casters. Would I not get to roll on a Flowing Though item, even though those are the only pieces in the game that can help my mana regen besides Alt Advancement? Mark my words, things are going to change for bards and we have to be adaptable.&quot;<br>
<br>
There are a lot of thoughts in this, so I will answer them as best as I can.  First of all, my quote was that except in specific circumstances bards will not wear this.  What you are describing here is a &quot;enchanter-suit&quot;, which is alternate equipment that you will wear in specific circumstances.  From my understanding of the way you have phrased this that means that this will be alternate equipment for you, whereas any int/wis caster will have this up except in specific circumstances.  What this means is that they are going to get more value out of it that a bard most likely will.  <br>
<br>
Let me put it to you a different way, except with an item that you are elligeable to roll on.  Lets say that for whatever reason, the discussion came up about clerics changes technically make them a melee class now.  So should they (and possibly other casters by association) be allowed to roll on an RBB?  After all it is a haste item and if clerics are going to melee more shouldn't they get it?  To an effect you can defend that position, but in most cases a cleric is not going to wear the belt, and will waste it in bank/backpack slots or sell it (my opinions here).  So would you think that it was fair to take an item that if you won you would wear all of the time, and give someone that might use it every once in a while (if they don't sell it) a chance to win it?  I think this is a pretty fair analogy.<br>
<br>
Combine that with the amount of stuff that bards can win (they have the highest percentage of dropped items that they can roll for, of any class), with the few things that casters can win.  Then you take in that casters are often asked to die repeatedly in a dragon raid, to regen to full mana quickly so that the raid can continue.  My personal highest death count on a dragon raid (not kcog mind you) was 7 deaths, and I got 90% rezzes for all 7 of those deaths (lost over a yellow of xp).  On that particular raid I was not allowed to roll on anything that dropped, because none of the very rare casters items (and every item that a caster can use is among the rarest tier of items) dropped.  Now would it be fair to take a bard, who at worst dies once, has 4 bard rollable items drop, and then takes a roll on the 1 item that drops that a caster can use?  After an experience like that would you come back to a dragon raid?  If we don't get casters to come back to dragon raids can we continue to host them?<br>
<br>
When looking at these types of issues you have to look at the big picture sometimes.  It may not be the best personal shortterm picture for your class, but it is what is best for the organization.  That is why that rule is in place.  To be blunt we have few enough casters that come on the raids anyway because hardly any items drop.  On a Naggy raid there is exactly one item that I would bother to roll on as an Int Caster with decent but not great items, and that would be off of the Fire Giants.  Sure, there are a few odds and ends (an orb of Tishan with 7 str/sta anyone) that casters can roll on, but it would be a steep downgrade for anyone that even had bad equipment for the level.  So if you take one of the few items left to them, and let others roll on them where does that leave you next time when no clerics, or no enchanters show up?  It is nice to say that these raids are not about loots (and personally to me they aren't, I don't really care about winning myself, but wouldn't mind), but to a high percentage of the people you are depending on it is about the chance for loot.<br>
<br>
Haemish, will try and get to it tomorrow, or if not tomorrow next couple of days.  Been meaning to do it anyway, this just gives me more incentive. <p>Farrnusno <BR>
Guild Leader <BR>
Souls of the Valiant <BR>
KCoG Dragon Liaison</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uhaemish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Haemish</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>KCoG Founder</span><br>  Posts: 734<br> <font color=#8E9173>(9/17/02 8:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscouncildiscussions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=93.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.godwinclients.com/sd/haemish_new.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why be Greedy</span><hr size=1> I'll throw up another example, from the melee side, that kind of shows where I was going with this type of loot restriction when it first came up. <br>
<br>
Nagafen sometimes drops the Cloak of Flames. There aren't many items, even in Velious or Luclin, that are as wanted by a melee class as a cloak of flames. Excellent haste, good AC, and, if I recall correctly, some pretty good stat boosts. The item is an All/All item, though. I started the restriction (and the other raid leaders have followed suit on this) that only melee classes (which included bards) could roll on it. Sure, an int/wis caster can use it, but will they get the benefit from it that a melee would? Would many of them even wear it on a daily basis? It's one of those items that is really meant for a specific set of classes, so I restricted it to those classes. Yes, there are situations that a caster might use a COF, but chances are the melee will use that every day, as a bread and butter item. <br>
<br>
To get absolutely technical, any item that isn't NO DROP can be used by anyone to improve their gear. They could sell or trade an item they won't use for something they will use. My thoughts were that I'd rather people are rewarded with gear they'll use as opposed to sell. While being a merchant is part of the game (as was long before the Bazaar), the reason for killing a dragon is fun, glory and equipment. I understand you'd want the gear for an &quot;enchanter-suit&quot; situation, as I've seen a great bard who could do what an enchanter did just as well any day of the week. But he'd be the first to admit he wouldn't play that role every day. Bards are one of those classes that have never been handled right by Verant.... they are so versatile that no one knows how to &quot;classify&quot; them. I've usually put them in the hybrid category... the fact that they use less mana on a daily basis than most hybrids, as well as having less mana-required spells, puts them even more away from a caster class in my book.<br>
<br>
In the next few days, we'll be seeing some specific loot rules for our raids stickied to the top of the forums where they are relevant. Hopefully this will clear up any misconceptions before the raids begin about SOP.  <p>Haemish MacLennan<br>
Founder<Br>
Karana Council of Guilds<br>
"I don't play role-playing games to be a politician."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulautrec75.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lautrec75</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#8E9173>(9/17/02 10:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscouncildiscussions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=93.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://eqlive.station.sony.com/library/images/d_the_tribunal.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why be Greedy</span><hr size=1> &quot;Combine that with the amount of stuff that bards can win (they have the highest percentage of dropped items that they can roll for, of any class), with the few things that casters can win.&quot;<br>
<br>
Can win... if they drop. If they don't, and an ALL/ALL item drops you should have the right to roll. +Anyone+ should.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then you take in that casters are often asked to die repeatedly in a dragon raid, to regen to full mana quickly so that the raid can continue. My personal highest death count on a dragon raid (not kcog mind you) was 7 deaths, and I got 90% rezzes for all 7 of those deaths (lost over a yellow of xp). On that particular raid I was not allowed to roll on anything that dropped, because none of the very rare casters items (and every item that a caster can use is among the rarest tier of items) dropped.&quot;<br>
<br>
I feel sorry for you, my man. You got hosed, in my humble opinion. And so did everyone else who was not allowed to roll an ALL/ALL items. <br>
<br>
&quot;Now would it be fair to take a bard, who at worst dies once, has 4 bard rollable items drop, and then takes a roll on the 1 item that drops that a caster can use? After an experience like that would you come back to a dragon raid? If we don't get casters to come back to dragon raids can we continue to host them?&quot;<br>
<br>
If items are the only reason one comes to a raid, then they probably don't need to come back if it upsets them that much. If class specific items drop, those specific classes should roll. If an ALL/ALL item drops (regardless of whether it's considered a &quot;caster&quot; item, etc.) the ALL/ALL should be able to roll. You can abstain if you wish, but you should at least be allowed to roll. That's been my whole point on this entire post. I can't state it any more plain. I know I have the tide against me, but if there's no difference there is no growth. I'm not saying make the changes overnight. I'm simply saying try and look at a bigger picture. Why not even try it once? If anyone has anything to add to this please do. I'm very far from a perfect person and I look for help every chance I get. But all I see here is &quot;casters get shafted, so let's have a set of rules that allows them first rights.&quot; It's not about casters, melee or hybrids... it's about people. Personally I think a Wizard with a Cloak of Flames would be a pleasant change. But then again, what do I know.<br>
<br>
I'm just a bard.<br>
