<br>
One can't make a different set of loot rules every raid depending on what drops.  We have to make if fair in the long run for the people who attend regularly to encourage regular attendance.  If a bard attended all 5 of these raids they would have had the chance to roll on the following<br>
6 RBB<br>
2 Scale (now bard only rolls)<br>
1 horn (bard only)<br>
2 bracer<br>
2 pouch<br>
1 Crystalline Spear<br>
<br>
The eyepatch is UBER for int/wiz casters who would almost certainly keep it.  Allakazam has a pricecheck (not so accurate of course) of 24kpp for this!  IF a bard did win it, wouldn't most of them sell this and buy something that would help them a LOT more for their 24kpp?  According to KCoG Definitions, this falls into the greed side of things rather than the need side.<br>
<br>
I agree wholeheartedly that there is a big difference between &quot;Use it every day&quot; and &quot;My special XXX suit&quot;.  I see the &quot;special suit&quot; as about half way between &quot;everyday equipment&quot; and &quot;sell to buy something else&quot;.<br>
<br>
I see two defining and complementary themes for loot at KCoG plus an all important rule 3:<br>
<br>
1) Need before greed (NBG) = Use it all the time &gt; Use it sometimes but mostly not &gt; sell for plat<br>
<br>
2) Fairness = Try to have at least SOMETHING for everyone<br>
<br>
3) The raid leader sets loot rules.  To make a moderatly absurd example, If the raid leader wants to distribute the loot in alpahbetical order and this is stated in the raid signup and raid rules...  That's the way it's gonna be.<br>
<br>
Maybe it's just me?<br>
